caption: Quiet park, small play area for children. Public toilet is not clean or supplied, but is free. Lots of benches to sit and enjoy a break.
Nice small square. Could be difficult to find a free seat, but if you will be lucky - very calm and cozy place.
Unique üí´ ‚Ä¶
The perfect spot for a picnic lunch while staying at the Hotel Lorette. Only after you‚Äôve visited re des martyres for your vino and pastries ü§§ü§§ ‚Ä¶
Nice park, only the experience was spoiled by boys with loud music and consumption of cannabis.
A good resting place and park in the middle of all the residential area of the 9th arrondissement. But expect lots of children playing there once school ends.
Small park but silence good and for 2 to 7 year children play good park
A lovely, secluded and quiet square just near Place St Georges in the 9th Arr.  Just sit and relax
A small but lovely park to take a small break
My favorite little Park, just to get away from it all.
Ras

Square with games for children and benches for parents. Going up, a more peaceful place to read, draw, discuss, it's wooded and flowery with a beautiful period building, guaranteed character! In case of rain, a large covered area for shelter is practical.
Delightful public park, small and surrounded by beautiful houses (envy having the view below). There are also games for children.
A very pleasant place to relax with a book or paint or just let the sun's rays fall on the skin to the rhythm of the birdsong ‚òÄÔ∏è

In this neighborhood, a place to discover to recharge your batteries. Greenery, benches in the sun or shade, calm. You can sit there and enjoy the architecture of the building, the small courtyard in case of rain and the flowers in spring.
Pleasant, this square is well wooded. Its tranquility invites reading or daydreaming. A small playground is available at the entrance to the square.

Small, very small "green lung" appreciable in Paris, quite well flowered. You can read there in peace, on the benches. Quiet except when ball games are played against the large door located at the entrance door... made of iron, what's more. Guaranteed headache in this case :-(
Nice, small park in the middle of a pretty busy area. Perfect for a little break. Very quiet! There is also a small playground at the entrance.
Green oasis in the middle of the hectic city. Ideal for a short break on one of the numerous benches set up all around! ü•ñ üç∑ don't forget!üòÅ ‚Ä¶
Very beautiful park, calming for a break before work
Lovely quiet park in the middle of the city, with benches. The benches are slanted, so you cannot always sit comfortably
A pleasant little square nestled between the mansions and the Saint-Georges theater. Very busy as soon as the sun comes out.
It's very quiet, well maintained. The gardener takes care of the plants and there are plenty of benches in the shade. At the entrance, a closed playground for small children.
A little greenery in the 9th is good! The square is nice, I tasted the grass and it is well nourished. The flowers are beautiful, some get confused but that's okay, it's not annoying.
Nice little park. Benches in the sun and shade. Play areas for children. Park away from the road.

Small square out of sight, Quiet, well-kept, with plenty of benches to enjoy the sun Ideal for reading or having a picnic before going to the Saint Georges Theater because right next to the Metro (line 12) A few minutes walk from Pigalle and Notre-Dame de Lorette
perfect when there are benches, watch out for falling chestnuts

Quiet enough to relax while doing nothing. I appreciated that the children's area was offset and enclosed, for safety and this way people who need peace and quiet are not bothered by the noise of children.

Very quiet and pleasant for a lunch break on a bench. Avoid on Wednesdays and at the end of the day when the place becomes very noisy with the arrival of children on the play area at the entrance to the garden.
Very nice and enjoy with children. If you like silence, go there in the morning. It's super relaxing and you can enjoy a concert organized by the birds

Airy square and nice facilities for children. Pedestrianization of the adjacent street which allows older children to play ball or cycle. Unfortunately, the square is not always super clean (broken bottles, leftovers from picnics, etc.)

Very pleasant place if you are looking for shade in case of heat but to avoid during school outing hours because the place is surrounded by buildings, which is resonant and very very noisy with the cries of the children.
Very pretty little garden in the 9th arrondissement of Paris near Place Pigalle and the New Athens district (19th century painters).
Nice little park to eat your sandwich from the Venezuelan next door. There are even public toilets and a water fountain. What more could you ask for? Benches? Yes there are plenty of them.

In this square, one day, I observed a child discovering pigeons. And he kept yelling: ‚ÄúWOOUASO. WOUASO‚Äù. I have the impression that he didn't necessarily want to catch them. But no doubt I projected part of my story onto him ‚Äì because when you really look at a child, you immediately plunge back into your childhood casually. In short, he suddenly wanted to gut these feathered beasts. Maybe he would become a serial killer I thought. ‚ÄúDon‚Äôt touch!‚Äù It's disgusting! ¬ª the one who seemed to be his mother called out to him. She yelled a lot too. I understood that the kid had identified with this way of expressing himself. And so, I showed the child how to attract the pigeon. Yes, with pieces of bread and, at that moment, suddenly jump on the bird.
Very quiet place, large with also a children's playground, lots of benches available. The perfect place to relax (eat, drink, rest)

Dirty toilets, a children's play area that is almost never cleaned, systematically broken benches, young people who smoke their firecrackers in front of the children, guys who come to drink, homeless people who sleep on the benches in the children's play area .... That's a lot for one of the only green spaces in the neighborhood. Finally when I say "green", I'm talking about the forbidden lawn. We are far from a big capital like Berlin or London...
Small square nestled right next to Place St Georges. Very supervised nature, but perfectly maintained. Small play area for children, less crowded than Square Montholon or Antwerp.
